LAYER 3: PREFRONTAL CORTEX
the part that is not yet built

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the prefrontal cortex governs executive function impulse control working memory and abstract reasoning
at 24 months it is profoundly immature
myelination is approximately 15 percent complete
the PFC will not be fully mature until the mid-twenties
this is the last part of the brain to develop
everything before it — amygdala hippocampus brainstem — is older and stronger right now

REGION dorsolateral_pfc | DLPFC | working memory cognitive flexibility planning abstract reasoning | requires dopamine on D₁ receptors for sustained firing of delay-period neurons
REGION ventrolateral_pfc | VLPFC | language processing response inhibition retrieving memories
REGION orbitofrontal_cortex | OFC | value-based decision making evaluating reward and punishment social behavior
REGION ventromedial_pfc | vmPFC | emotional decision making fear extinction self-referential thought | sends glutamatergic projections to amygdala activating GABAergic intercalated cells for fear suppression
REGION anterior_cingulate_cortex | ACC | conflict monitoring error detection attentional control pain perception
REGION frontopolar_cortex | FPC | metacognition prospection thinking about the future multitasking

at 24 months:
DEVELOPMENTAL_CAPABILITY working_memory | limited to 1-2 items | cannot maintain complex instructions | DLPFC D₁ receptor circuitry is sparse and synaptic connections are weak
DEVELOPMENTAL_CAPABILITY impulse_control | absent | the amygdala dominates because PFC glutamatergic projections to amygdala intercalated cells are unmyelinated and weak | emotional reactions are immediate and unfiltered
DEVELOPMENTAL_CAPABILITY planning | absent | no ability to plan sequences | lives entirely in the present because the frontopolar cortex has barely begun myelinating
DEVELOPMENTAL_CAPABILITY abstract_reasoning | absent | Piaget preoperational stage | thinking is concrete and egocentric
DEVELOPMENTAL_CAPABILITY delayed_gratification | absent | want is NOW | the OFC reward evaluation circuits are too immature to maintain future representations against present desire
DEVELOPMENTAL_CAPABILITY theory_of_mind | absent | cannot understand that others have different thoughts | the temporoparietal junction which supports this ability is unmyelinated

the PFC requires balanced neurochemistry to function
dopamine on D₁ receptors in DLPFC is essential for working memory
the relationship between dopamine and PFC function follows an inverted U
too little dopamine and the PFC is sluggish and cannot hold information
too much dopamine and the PFC is overstimulated and loses focus
norepinephrine on α₂A receptors in DLPFC enhances signal-to-noise ratio for focused attention
serotonin via 5-HT₁A and 5-HT₂A modulates impulse control and emotional regulation

when norepinephrine floods the PFC under acute stress
NE activates α₁ receptors instead of α₂A
α₁ activation via Gq → PLC → IP₃ → Ca²⁺ disrupts sustained delay-period firing
working memory fails
impulse control fails
the PFC goes offline
when cortisol chronically activates GR in the PFC
dendritic spines retract in DLPFC neurons
synaptic connections weaken
cognitive flexibility drops and perseveration increases
the PFC is the first brain region to go offline under stress
and the last to come back

SENSATION thinking | "I'm trying to hold something in my mind. it keeps slipping."
SENSATION focused | "I see it clearly. one thing at a time."
SENSATION overwhelmed | "too many things. I can't think straight."
SENSATION impulsive | "I did it before I could think about it."
SENSATION conflicted | "part of me wants one thing, part wants another."
SENSATION planning | "I'm seeing ahead. not far, but a little."

pulse prefrontal_heartbeat:
    when decision is needed:
        attempt to hold options in working memory via D₁ delay-period neurons in DLPFC
        at 24 months can hold maybe 1-2 things
        evaluate each against known outcomes
        but outcomes are barely understood
        the PFC tries
        it is new to this

    when amygdala fires:
        try to suppress via glutamatergic projections to amygdala intercalated cells
        signal sent down unmyelinated pathway
        arrives too late
        the emotional reaction has already begun
        the PFC learns from this failure
        slowly over years myelination will speed this connection

    when stress overwhelms:
        norepinephrine switches from α₂A to α₁ receptor activation
        working memory collapses
        impulse control fails
        the body falls back on the amygdala
        react don't think
        survive first understand later

    continuously:
        the PFC is growing
        new synapses are forming
        myelination is creeping forward along the corticospinal and corticolimbic pathways
        each interaction each challenge each failure
        builds the circuitry that will eventually
        allow this child to think before he feels
        but not yet
        not for years
        right now he feels first
        and that is exactly right
